passages.text: FY25 Results: Increasingly Cautious on Ongoing Cost- Out Uncertainty and Pricing Strategy shift; Downgrade to Neutral
DMP.AX 12m Price Target: A\\$17.50 Price: A\\$14.94 Upside: 17.1%

Result: DMP reported in- line FY25 results with group Network Sales of \(\) 4,153m\((- 0.1\% /0.6\%vs.\) GSe/VA Consensus) and Group EBIT - 5\% YoY at\) \ \(198m\) \((- 2.2\% / - 1.3\%vs.\) GSe/VA Cons. DMP also reported lower- than- expected FY26 7- wk Group SSSg of \(- 0.9\%\) (vs. \(- 1.3\%\) pcp) with strong growth in Germany, Benelux and Malaysia offset by weaker Japan, ANZ and France. GS View: While we view mgmt's store closure program across underperforming stores in Asia and Japan and focus on unit economics as prudent, we are cautious on the short- medium term due to:

Every Day Value: Shift from a sales- focused strategy to prioritizing franchisee EBITDA growth by transitioning pricing architecture from Discounting to Every Day Low Pricing (EDLP). This represents a fundamental shift from DMP's historical coupon- led and offer- based pricing strategy and may impact on sales volumes in short- to- medium term as customers adjust. Consequently, we lower FY26- 28e Network Sales by \(2\%\) to \(5\%\) .

Degree and Timing of Cost- out Remains Uncertain: Following DMP's July Investor Q&A, mgmt flagged cost reductions targeting IT, Head Office, and SG&A costs. However, the lack of detail around pace, magnitude, and Franchisee/DMP sharing creates uncertainty about the timeline for improving franchisee/DMP profitability. We lower EBIT margins by 80- 110bps.

Our Sales and EBIT are lowered \(2 - 5\%\) and \(11 - 15\%\) for FY26- 28e reflecting 80- 110bp EBIT margin cuts. Our valuation methodology is unchanged with SOTP multiple lowered for ANZ to 12x (from 13x) and Asia- JP+TW) to 9x (from 10x) reflecting ANZ uncertainty and Asia underperformance. TP A\\$17.5 (vs. prev A\\$23.9) implies \(17\%\) upside. DMP trading on 11.6x FY26 PE. Downgrade to Neutral.

Reflecting the above, we make the following key earnings changes:

Lower Asia in FY26- 28e given continued weak performance in Japan and CEO recruitment ongoing. Lower Group FY26- 28e Network Sales \(- 2\%\) to \(- 5\%\) to reflect short- medium term uncertainty amid transition to Everyday Value pricing strategy. Confidence on cost savings flowing to DMP lower following FY25 result, therefore we lower Group EBIT margin by \(80 - 110\) bps.
Exhibit 5:We lower Group EBIT-11% to \(-15\%\) FY26-28e Earnings Changes
Source:Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Our Valuation methodology is unchanged. Our SOTP EV/EBIT multiple for ANZ is lowered from \(13x\) to \(12x\) reflecting uncertainty around the impact of the pricing strategy shift. Reflecting the ongoing challenges in Japan amid mass store closures and ongoing recruitment for Japan CEO, we lower Asia EV/EBIT multiple to \(9.0x\) (vs prev. \(10.0x\) ) to reflect continued uncertainty weighing down regional performance. Our blended EV/EBIT multiple now sits at \(11.2x\) vs peer average of \(11.6x\) . Therefore, our revised 12m TP of \(A\$ 17.5\) (vs. prev \(A\$ 23.9\) ) implies \(17\%\) upside.
Since we added DMP to our Buy List on July 19, 2024, the stock is down \(56\%\) vs. ASX200 up \(13\%\) . We attribute this to the surprise CEO departure, lack of clarity around
cost out targets' magnitude/timing, uncertain impact of pricing strategy change, and negative trading update at FY25 results.

Turnaround in Europe/Japan execution (+): If Domino's is able to restore performance across underperforming Japan and European stores by improving franchisee profitability and following the closure of several loss- making stores across the Group's regional network, we would expect improved store economics.

Uncertain cost- out execution (- ): If Domino's is unable to effectively execute its cost- out program, franchisee profitability levels may remain challenged potentially leading to further closure of loss- making stores across their network and EBIT margin pressures.

Deterioration in strong performing regions (- ): DMP has reflected positive performance over past 12m in Australia and Germany. However should performance in either/both of these regions deteriorate, DMP profitability may be lowered and/or store roll- out plans may be delayed.
Improving Macro Conditions (+): An improvement in macroeconomic conditions and interest rate cuts could stimulate consumer spending trends, positively impacting Domino's sales volumes.
Domino's Pizza Enterprises (DMP) is the largest franchisee of the Domino's Pizza Inc.

(NYSE:DPZ) parent brand and has a footprint primarily in ANZ, Europe and Japan. We believe management's focus on franchisee profitability through closure of 312 locations largely in Japan/France will help to material improve the quality of the network and help franchisee profitability. DMP's fundamental Shift in Pricing Strategy from Discount-led to Every Day Value and with Degree and Timing of Cost-out uncertain, we are now cautious on the short-medium term outlook for improving store/unit economics. Stock is trading below long term average PE ratio. Neutral

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
